Human Activity Recognition - Predicting how well weight lifting excercises were performed using sensory data

Practical Machine Learning Final Assignment

atomasovszky

Synopsis

The goal of this work is to use on-body sensor data to predict whether a particular excercise is performed correctly. The 6 participants of the study our data is coming from were equippped with movement sensors on their arm, forearm, a belt sensor on their waist and one on their dumbell, and theyve been asked to perform weight lifting in a proper way (classe = A), and with some common mistakes (classe = {B, C, D, E}).

Feature selection

Besides the obvious ones (ids, timestamps, etc.) we also left summary variables out as they have missing values for most of the records.

summary_vars <- grep(
    pattern = "^kurtosis|^skewness|^max|^min|^amplitude|^var|^avg|^stddev", 
    x       = names(train),
    value   = TRUE
)

variables_to_omit <- c(
    summary_vars,
    grep("window|V1|user|timestamp", names(train), value = TRUE)
)

train_clean <- train[, .SD, .SDcols = setdiff(names(train), variables_to_omit)]

Training the model using cross validation

We chose to use random forest for the prediction task over CART and rpart as it corrects for the latter two methods tendency to overfitting and thus we expected to reach a better bias-variance tradeoff. In order to estimate the out-of-sample error (accuracy) we used repeated k-fold cross validation with 10 folds and 3 repetitions for each of them. We estimated the error by the average of the models accuracy on these 30 folds.

As the training of the random forest model would have took too long, we only used 5000 randomly selected cases from the original training dataset. We also set the ntrees parameter to 50, so the algorithm created only 50 bootstrap samples and trees using them.

set.seed(20190428)

cl <- makePSOCKcluster(10)
registerDoParallel(cl)

cv_control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", 10, 3, allowParallel = TRUE)

train_clean_sample <- sample(1:nrow(train_clean), 5000)

rf_train <- train(
    form      = classe ~ .,
    data      = train_clean[train_clean_sample],
    method    = "rf",
    ntree     = 50,
    trControl = cv_control
)

stopImplicitCluster()
registerDoSEQ()

rf_train
